# Debugging Strategies

---

## 1. Read the Error Message First
Don't guess — the error message tells you exactly what went wrong and where.

```
TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'name')
    at getUser (app.js:5:20)
    at main (app.js:12:3)
```

- Error type: `TypeError`
- What: accessing `.name` on `undefined`
- Where: `app.js` line 5
- Go there first.

---

## 2. `console.log` — Inspect Values

Add logs before the crash to see what data looks like.

```js
function getFullName(user) {
  console.log('user received:', user); // inspect here
  return `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`;
}
```

Log at key points to trace the flow:
```js
function processOrder(order) {
  console.log('1. Processing order:', order.id);
  const items = filterAvailable(order.items);
  console.log('2. Available items:', items);
  const total = calculateTotal(items);
  console.log('3. Total:', total);
  return { items, total };
}
```

---

## 3. Use `console.table` for Arrays of Objects

```js
const users = [
  { name: 'Bruce', score: 82 },
  { name: 'Clark', score: 45 },
];
console.table(users); // much easier to read than console.log
```

---

## 4. Isolate the Problem

Reduce the failing code to the smallest possible example.

```js
// Broken in context:
const result = getUser(userId).profile.name.toUpperCase();

// Isolate each step:
const user = getUser(userId);
console.log('user:', user);           // null?

const profile = user.profile;
console.log('profile:', profile);     // undefined?

const name = profile.name;
console.log('name:', name);           // '' ?
```

---

## 5. Check Assumptions

Most bugs come from assuming data looks a certain way when it doesn't.

```js
// Assumption: user.tags is an array
// Reality: it might be undefined or null

function getTags(user) {
  console.log('tags type:', typeof user.tags, user.tags);
  return user.tags.join(', '); // crash if undefined
}

// Fix after checking
function getTags(user) {
  if (!Array.isArray(user.tags)) return '';
  return user.tags.join(', ');
}
```

---

## 6. Use the Node.js Debugger

Add `debugger` to pause execution and inspect state.

```js
function processUser(user) {
  debugger; // execution pauses here in debugger mode
  return user.name.toUpperCase();
}
```

Run with:
```bash
node --inspect app.js
```

Then open `chrome://inspect` in Chrome.

Or use VS Code's built-in debugger — add breakpoints by clicking the line number.

---

## 7. `typeof` and `instanceof` Checks

When a crash is hard to reproduce, add type guards to expose unexpected values:

```js
function safeProcess(data) {
  console.log('type:', typeof data);
  console.log('is array:', Array.isArray(data));
  console.log('value:', data);
}
```

---

## 8. Binary Search for Bugs

When you don't know where the bug is, comment out half the code, check if the bug persists, then narrow it down.

```js
function pipeline(data) {
  const step1 = transform(data);
  // console.log('after step1:', step1);
  const step2 = validate(step1);
  // console.log('after step2:', step2);
  const step3 = format(step2);
  return step3;
}

// Uncomment logs one at a time until you find where data goes wrong
```

---

## 9. Google the Exact Error Message
Copy the error message (without the file name/line number) and search:
```
TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'map')
```

Add `mdn` or `stack overflow` to your search for faster results.

---

## 10. Take a Break
If you've been stuck for more than 20 minutes, step away. Fresh eyes catch bugs faster.

---

## Debugging Checklist

1. ✅ Read the full error message
2. ✅ Go to the exact line in the stack trace
3. ✅ `console.log` the value just before the crash
4. ✅ Check what type/shape you're assuming vs what you're getting
5. ✅ Isolate — write the smallest test case that reproduces it
6. ✅ If stuck, search the exact error message